edu.rit.util

Class MultiSet<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.rit.util.MultiSet<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - Element data type.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Streamable

    public class MultiSet<E>
extends Object
implements Streamable
    Class MultiSet provides a multiset of elements. A multiset is a set in which each element may appear more than once. An element's multiplicity (an integer greater than or equal to 0) is the number of times the element appears in the multiset. The element must be an object suitable for use in a hashed data structure; that is, the element class must define the equals() and hashCode() methods properly. Elements must not be null. Once an element is stored in a multiset, the state of the element must not be altered.

    The multiset calls the protected getPair() method to make an element-multiplicity pair being added to the multiset. The multiset calls the protected copyElement() method to make a copy of an element being added to the multiset. The default is to copy just the element reference. This behavior can be changed by overriding the aforementioned methods in a subclass of class MultiSet.

    Class MultiSet is streamable. For object streaming to work properly, the element class must be streamable or serializable.

    Note: Class MultiSet is not multiple thread safe.

      • forEachItemDo

        public void forEachItemDo(Action<IntPair<E>> action)
        Perform the given action on each element in this multiset. For each element in this multiset in an unspecified order, the given action's run() method is called, passing in a pair consisting of the element (key) and the element's multiplicity (value). The state of the element must not be altered. The multiplicity may be altered. If the multiplicity is set to a value ≤ 0, the element is removed from this multiset.

        Warning: If the action adds elements to or removes elements from the multiset, other than by setting the multiplicity, the forEachItemDo() method's behavior is unspecified.

        Parameters:
        action - Action.

      • forEachItemDo

        public <R> R forEachItemDo(ActionResult<IntPair<E>,R> action)
        Perform the given action on each element in this multiset and return a result. For each element in this multiset in an unspecified order, the given action's run() method is called, passing in a pair consisting of the element (key) and the element's multiplicity (value). The state of the element must not be altered. The multiplicity may be altered. If the multiplicity is set to a value ≤ 0, the element is removed from this multiset. After all the elements have been processed, the given action's result() method is called, and its result is returned.

        Warning: If the action adds elements to or removes elements from the multiset, other than by setting the multiplicity, the forEachItemDo() method's behavior is unspecified.

        Type Parameters:
        R - Result data type.
        Parameters:
        action - Action.
        Returns:
        Result of processing all the set elements.

      • toArray

        public IntPair<E>[] toArray(IntPair<E>[] array)
        Store this multiset's elements in the given array. Each unique element is stored as a pair consisting of the element (key) and the element's multiplicity (value). The elements are stored in an unspecified order. The first element is stored at index 0, the second element at index 1, and so on. The number of array elements stored is array.length. If this multiset contains fewer than array.length unique elements, the remaining array elements are set to null.

        The toArray() method stores references to this multiset's element-multiplicity pairs in the given array. The states of the elements stored in the array must not be altered. The multiplicities stored in the array must not be altered.

        Parameters:
        array - Array in which to store elements.
        Returns:
        The given array is returned.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - (unchecked exception) Thrown if array is null.

      • toArray

        public IntPair<E>[] toArray(IntPair<E>[] array,
                   int off,
                   int len)
        Store this multiset's elements in the given array. Each unique element is stored as a pair consisting of the element (key) and the element's multiplicity (value). The elements are stored in an unspecified order. The first element is stored at index off, the second element at index off+1, and so on. The number of array elements stored is len. If this multiset contains fewer than len unique elements, the remaining array elements are set to null.

        The toArray() method stores references to this multiset's element-multiplicity pairs in the given array. The states of the elements stored in the array must not be altered. The multiplicities stored in the array must not be altered.

        Parameters:
        array - Array in which to store elements.
        off - Index at which to store first element.
        len - Number of elements to store.
        Returns:
        The given array is returned.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - (unchecked exception) Thrown if array is null.
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - (unchecked exception) Thrown if off < 0, len < 0, or off+len > array.length.

      • getPair

        protected IntPair<E> getPair(E key,
                 int value)
        Create a pair containing the given element and multiplicity. Whenever class MultiSet needs to create a pair, it does so by calling this method.

        The getPair() method in class MultiSet returns an instance of class IntPair<E>. The given element is copied using the copyElement() method. A subclass of class MultiSet can override the getPair() method to return something else. Possibilities include:

        • Return an instance of a subclass of class IntPair<E>, in which the equals() and hashCode() methods have been overridden to implement a different pair equality criterion.

        • Return an instance of a subclass of class IntPair<E>, in which the writeOut() and readIn() methods have been overridden to implement different streaming behavior.
        Parameters:
        key - Key (element).
        value - Value (multiplicity).
        Returns:
        Pair consisting of (key, value).

      • copyElement

        protected E copyElement(E elem)
        Copy the given element. The copyElement() method in class MultiSet merely returns the elem reference; this makes a shallow copy. A subclass of class MultiSet can override the copyElement() method to return something else. Possibilities include:

        • Return a clone of the element, which makes a deep copy.

        • Return an instance of a subclass of the element's class, in which the writeOut() and readIn() methods have been overridden to implement different streaming behavior.
        Parameters:
        elem - Set element to copy.
        Returns:
        Copy of elem.
